Yes a human language or grammar doesn&#x27;t come into being the same way a programming language does, but the notion of correctness still exists and I&#x27;d probably define it as:<p>Correct === Tradition + Lots &#x27;o&#x27; Time<p>And Matt wasn&#x27;t arguing this, but I have to link to Eric Lippert whenever I can so:<p>The idea programming language isn&#x27;t &#x27;correct&#x27; is kinda wonky. As I learned from Eric Lippert&#x27;s [Three umpires](<a href="http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ericlippert/archive/2009/11/09/three-umpires.aspx" rel="nofollow">http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ericlippert/archive/2009/11/09/three...</a>):<p><pre><code>  Three baseball umpires are having lunch together. 

  The first umpire says &quot;Well, a lot of them are balls, and a lot of them are 
  strikes, but I always calls &#x27;em as I sees &#x27;em.&quot;

  The second umpire says &quot;Hmph. I calls &#x27;em as they are.&quot;

  The third umpire slowly looks at his two colleagues and declares &quot;They ain&#x27;t 
  nothin&#x27; until I calls &#x27;em.&quot;
</code></pre>
When a designed language is presented to you, you can&#x27;t really argue about correctness, only suitability to a particular purpose or taste.
